  §3 SURVIVES, ON PUBLIC DATA, WITH THE CORRECT NULL.

  Under random SNP loss chi^2 RISES. With a thin population in the
  extract it FALLS -- below every one of 20 random-loss replicates at
  the same basis. The surviving SNPs are that genome's coverage
  footprint: an ascertained subset, not a random one.

  RESTATE THE DIAGNOSTIC:
    NOT  'chi^2 fell faster than the SNP count'   (the premise is false)
    BUT  'chi^2 fell when random loss says it should have risen'

